# Branch protection for {{CONSUMER_NAME}}

Apply these settings to `main` once the remote exists. Templated from
pgas's HANDOVER.md "Branch-protection settings" and pgas-rag's
equivalent.

## One-shot setup (gh CLI)

```bash
gh api -X PUT \
  repos/{{GH_OWNER}}/{{CONSUMER_NAME}}/branches/main/protection \
  --raw-field 'required_status_checks[strict]=true' \
  --raw-field 'required_status_checks[contexts][]=ci' \
  --raw-field 'required_status_checks[contexts][]=cheap-gates' \
  --raw-field 'enforce_admins=false' \
  --raw-field 'required_pull_request_reviews[required_approving_review_count]=0' \
  --raw-field 'required_pull_request_reviews[require_code_owner_reviews]=true' \
  --raw-field 'required_linear_history=true' \
  --raw-field 'allow_force_pushes=false' \
  --raw-field 'allow_deletions=false' \
  --raw-field 'restrictions=null'
```

The `required_approving_review_count=0` is the **solo-dev** posture:
the orchestrator self-merges after their own review. Bump to `1`
when a second human reviewer joins.

## Sub-agent branch convention

Per CLAUDE.md "Agent behavior — orchestrator role", sub-agents commit
to branches prefixed:

- `feat/<short-slug>` — new feature
- `fix/<short-slug>` — bug fix
- `chore/<short-slug>` — deps, scaffolding
- `docs/<short-slug>` — docs-only
- `release/v<X.Y.Z>` — version cut

`main` is protected; sub-agents NEVER push directly.

## Required CI gates

- `ci` — the main CI workflow (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`)
- `cheap-gates` — the cheap-gates no-op companion job (mirror of
  pgas's pattern) so branch protection can require it cleanly

Add more gates as they land. Per pgas's pattern, every required gate
has a corresponding `-noop.yml` so a path-filtered skip can still
mark the gate green.
